<subSubSection id="02C66578FFFAFFBBFF3D9FCB682479C7" pageId="23" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFAFFBBFF3D9FCB69C27947" blockId="23.[151,756,911,1191]" pageId="23" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFAFFBBFF3D9FCB68057EC6" bold="true" box="[151,264,911,935]" pageId="23" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is distinguished by a very elongated, compressed and slightly tapering test. The chambers are numerous, very distinct, slightly inflated and increasing gradually in height from the earlier chambers to the later ones.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFAFFBBFF3D986A682479C7" blockId="23.[151,756,911,1191]" pageId="23" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFAFFBBFF3D986A68D87927" bold="true" box="[151,469,1070,1094]" pageId="23" pageNumber="37">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It is recorded in the Maastrichtian of southwestern Desert of 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFAFFBBFDEE980B6B897906" box="[580,644,1103,1127]" name="Egypt" pageId="23" pageNumber="37">Egypt</collectingCountry>
by LUGER (1985). It is recorded in the Maastrichtian of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
